      "writtenOn": "2021-05-28T09:26:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Here are some problems I found from the snippet.\n\n(1) the line.Delimiter is buffered only if the buffer is going to be truncated w/ the delimiter at L44.\n\nTherefore, If an entry has [{Value: \"line 1\", delimiter: \"\\n\"}, {\"line 2\", \"delimiter: \"\\n\"}], the generated payload would be \"line 1line 2\" w/o the delimiter.\n\n(2) it updates b.completeLineEndsAt at L45, only if the buffer is going to exceeds the limit w/ the delimiter. Let\u0027s say that a stream has the following entries.\n\n[1]: {Lines: [{Value: \"line 1\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}, {Value: \"line 2\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}, {\"Value\": \"lin\", Delimiter: \"\"}]}\n[2]: {Lines: e is going to be tooooooo long\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}\n\nAfter processing [1], it would still have completeLineEndsAt with 0, as sum() of the lines are still \u003c MaxPayload, but it is incorrect.\nWhen it processes [2], it will just add the line of [2] to the existing buffer and truncate the entire buffer. Thus, the generated cl.Entry would be as follow.\n\n[a]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line 1line 2line is going to be tooo\\n\"}\n\nHowever, what it should have generated is\n[a]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line 1\\nline 2\"}\n[b]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line 3 is toooo\"}\n\n(Note that [b] has no \\n although the line of [2] has \\n delimiter. If it\u0027s going to be truncated, printing the delimiter just reduces the length of the line before truncation for no reason.)\n\n(3) (2) can also cause a string to be truncated incorrectly.\n\n[1]: {Lines: [{Value: \"line 1\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}, {Value: \"line 2\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}, {\"Value\": \"lin\", Delimiter: \"\"}]}\n[2]: {Lines: e is not too long by itself\", Delimiter: \"\\n\"}\n\nLet\u0027s say that\n- sum([\"line 1\", \"line 2\", \"line is not too long by itself\"]) \u003e MaxPayload\n- sum([\"line 1\", \"line 2\"]) \u003c MaxPayload\n- sum([\"line is not too long by itself\"]) \u003c MaxPayload\n\nthus, it should generate the following cl.Entry{}s w/o truncation.\n[a]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line 1\\nline 2\"}\n[b]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line is not too long by itself\"}\n\nHowever, the snippet would generate the following entry.\n[a]: cl.Entry{Payload: \"line 1\\nline 2\\nline is not too lo\"}  # truncated",
